The table gives [[crustal abundance]]s of the elements commonly to rarely recognised as metalloids.<ref>[[#Lide|Lide 2005]]; [[#Wiberg2001|Wiberg 2001, p.&nbsp;423: At]]</ref> Some other elements are included for comparison: oxygen and xenon (the most and least abundant elements with stable isotopes); iron and the coinage metals copper, silver and gold; and rhenium, the least abundant stable metal (aluminium is normally the most abundant metal). Various abundance estimates have been published; these often disagree to some extent.<ref>[[#Cox|Cox 1997, pp. 182<U+2012>86]]</ref>

===Extraction===
The recognised metalloids can be obtained by [[redox|chemical reduction]] of either their oxides or their [[sulfide]]s. Simpler or more complex extraction methods may be employed depending on the starting form and economic factors.<ref>[[#MacKay2002|MacKay, MacKay & Henderson 2002, p.&nbsp;204]]</ref> Boron is routinely obtained by reducing the trioxide with magnesium: B<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> + 3 Mg <U+2192> 2 B + 3MgO; after secondary processing the resulting brown powder has a purity of up to 97%.<ref>[[#Baudis|Baudis 2012, pp.&nbsp;207<U+2013>8]]</ref> Boron of higher purity (> 99%) is prepared by heating volatile boron compounds, such as BCl<sub>3</sub> or BBr<sub>3</sub>, either in a hydrogen atmosphere (2 BX<sub>3</sub> + 3 H<sub>2</sub> <U+2192> 2 B + 6 HX) or to the point of [[thermal decomposition]]. Silicon and germanium are obtained from their oxides by heating the oxide with carbon or hydrogen: SiO<sub>2</sub> + C <U+2192> Si + CO<sub>2</sub>; GeO<sub>2</sub> + 2 H<sub>2</sub> <U+2192> Ge + 2 H<sub>2</sub>O. Arsenic is isolated from its pyrite (FeAsS) or arsenical pyrite (FeAs<sub>2</sub>) by heating; alternatively, it can be obtained from its oxide by reduction with carbon: 2 As<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> + 3 C <U+2192> 2 As + 3 CO<sub>2</sub>.<ref>[[#Wiberg2001|Wiberg 2001, p.&nbsp;741]]</ref> Antimony is derived from its sulfide by reduction with iron: Sb<sub>2</sub>S<sub>3</sub> <U+2192> 2 Sb + 3 FeS. Tellurium is prepared from its oxide by dissolving it in aqueous NaOH, yielding tellurite, then by [[electrolytic reduction]]: TeO<sub>2</sub> + 2 NaOH <U+2192> Na<sub>2</sub>TeO<sub>3</sub> + H<sub>2</sub>O;<ref>[[#Chizhikov1968|Chizhikov & Shchastlivyi 1968, p.&nbsp;96]]</ref> Na<sub>2</sub>TeO<sub>3</sub> + H<sub>2</sub>O <U+2192> Te + 2 NaOH + O<sub>2</sub>.<ref>[[#Greenwood2002|Greenwood & Earnshaw 2002, pp.&nbsp;140<U+2013>1, 330, 369, 548<U+2013>9, 749: B, Si, Ge, As, Sb, Te]]</ref> Another option is reduction of the oxide by roasting with carbon: TeO<sub>2</sub> + C <U+2192> Te + CO<sub>2</sub>.<ref>[[#Kudryavtsev1974|Kudryavtsev 1974, p.&nbsp;158]]</ref>

Production methods for the elements less frequently recognised as metalloids involve natural processing, electrolytic or chemical reduction, or irradiation. Carbon (as graphite) occurs naturally and is extracted by crushing the parent rock and floating the lighter graphite to the surface. Aluminium is extracted by dissolving its oxide Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> in molten [[cryolite]] Na<sub>3</sub>AlF<sub>6</sub> and then by high temperature electrolytic reduction. Selenium is produced by roasting its coinage metal selenides X<sub>2</sub>Se (X = Cu, Ag, Au) with [[soda ash]] to give the selenite: X<sub>2</sub>Se + O<sub>2</sub> + Na<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>3</sub> <U+2192> Na<sub>2</sub>SeO<sub>3</sub> + 2 X + CO<sub>2</sub>; the selenide is neutralized by sulfuric acid H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>4</sub> to give [[selenous acid]] H<sub>2</sub>SeO<sub>3</sub>; this is reduced by bubbling with [[sulfur dioxide|SO<sub>2</sub>]] to yield elemental selenium. Polonium and astatine are produced in minute quantities by irradiating bismuth.<ref>[[#Greenwood2002|Greenwood & Earnshaw 2002, pp.&nbsp;271, 219, 748<U+2013>9, 886: C, Al, Se, Po, At]]; [[#Wiberg2001|Wiberg 2001, p.&nbsp;573: Se]]</ref>

===Cost===
The recognised metalloids and their closer neighbours mostly cost less than silver; only polonium and astatine are more expensive than gold. As of 5 April 2014, prices for small samples (up to 100 g) of silicon, antimony and tellurium, and graphite, aluminium and selenium, average around one third the cost of silver (US$1.5 per gram or about $45 an ounce). Boron, germanium and arsenic samples average about three-and-a-half times the cost of silver.{{#tag:ref|Sample prices of gold, in comparison, start at roughly thirty-five times that of silver. Based on sample prices for B, C, Al, Si, Ge, As, Se, Ag, Sb, Te and Au available on-line from [http://www.alfa.com/en/gp160w.pgm Alfa Aesa]; [http://www.goodfellow.com/catalogue/GFCatL.php?ewd_token=d9JJMyYK0a7QlDSc171OUVMREOSDVO&n=FkZgkaaF0WMB5EJhaP0zaLTZIN5ixG&ewd_urlNo=GFCatalogue2&next=Period Goodfellow]; [http://www.elementsales.com/pl_element.htm Metallium]; and [http://www.unitednuclear.com/index.php?main_page=index&cPath=16_17_69 United Nuclear Scientific].|group=n}} Polonium is available for about $100 per [[microgram]], which is $100,000,000 a gram.<ref>[[#United|United Nuclear 2013]]</ref> Zalutsky and Pruszynski<ref>[[#Zalutsky|Zalutsky & Pruszynski 2011, p. 181]]</ref> estimate a similar cost for producing astatine. Prices for the applicable elements traded as commodities tend to range from two to three times cheaper than the sample price (Ge), to nearly three thousand times cheaper (As).{{#tag:ref|Based on [[spot price]]s for Al, Si, Ge, As, Sb, Se, and Te available on-line from [http://www.fastmarkets.com/minor-metals FastMarkets: Minor Metals]; [http://www.fastmarkets.com/base-metals Fast Markets: Base Metals]; [http://pv.energytrend.com/ EnergyTrend: PV Market Status, Polysilicon]; and [http://www.metal-pages.com/metals/arsenic/metal-prices-news-information/ Metal-Pages: Arsenic metal prices, news and information].|group=n}}

